Some shuffled with their ankles manacled and others were chained by their legs to large metal wheels to prevent escape.
“This place is neither a rehab or an Islamic school because you can see it for yourselves,” Kaduna state’s police commissioner, Ali Janga, told reporters.
“The children gathered here are from all over the country… some of them were even chained.
Islamic schools, known as Almajiris, are common across the mostly Muslim north of Nigeria – a country that is roughly evenly split between followers of Christianity and Islam.
Akintola said Islamic schools needed funding to train teachers and improve the buildings.